T1  - Asymmetric Tournaments, Equal Opportunity Laws, and Affirmative Action: Some Experimental Results*
PY  - 1992
Y1  - 1992/05/01
DO  - 10.2307/2118480
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 107
IS  - 2
SP  - 511
EP  - 539
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - This paper assesses whether affirmative action programs and equal opportunity laws affect the output of economic agents. More precisely, we find that equal opportunity laws and affirmative action programs always benefit disadvantaged groups. Equal opportunity laws also increase the effort levels of all subjects and hence the profits of the tournament administrator (usually the firm). The effects of affirmative action programs depend on the severity of a group's cost disadvantage. When the cost disadvantage is severe, these programs significantly increase effort levels (and hence profits). The opposite is true when the disadvantage is slight.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2118480
ER  - 



