TY  - JOUR
AU  - Peltzman, Sam
T1  - Voters as Fiscal Conservatives*
PY  - 1992
Y1  - 1992/05/01
DO  - 10.2307/2118475
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 107
IS  - 2
SP  - 327
EP  - 361
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Voters penalize federal and state spending growth. This is the central result of my analysis of voting behavior in Presidential, Senatorial, and gubernatorial elections from 1950–1988. The composition of federal spending growth seems irrelevant. The vote loss to the President's party from an extra dollar of defense or nondefense spending is the same. However, in gubernatorial elections, expansion of state welfare spending exacts a disproportionate political price. Deficit financing of federal or state spending does not appear to matter politically. I conclude by discussing the obvious question of why government budgets have grown in the face of this voter hostility.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2118475
ER  - 



