T1  - Market Structure and the Nature of Price Rigidity: Evidence from the Market for Consumer Deposits*
PY  - 1992
Y1  - 1992/05/01
DO  - 10.2307/2118485
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 107
IS  - 2
SP  - 657
EP  - 680
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Panel data on consumer bank deposit interest rates reveal asymmetric impacts of market concentration on the dynamic adjustment of prices to shocks. Banks in concentrated markets are slower to raise interest rates on deposits in response to rising market interest rates, but are faster to reduce them in response to declining market interest rates. Thus, banks with market power skim off surplus on movements in both directions. Since deposit interest rates are inversely related to the price charged by banks for deposits, the results suggest that downward price rigidity and upward price flexibility are a consequence of market concentration.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2118485
ER  - 



