TY  - JOUR
AU  - Weitzman, Martin L.
T1  - On Diversity*
PY  - 1992
Y1  - 1992/05/01
DO  - 10.2307/2118476
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 107
IS  - 2
SP  - 363
EP  - 405
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - An oft-repeated goal in many contexts is the “preservation of diversity.” But what is the diversity function to be optimized? This paper shows how a reasonable measure of the “value of diversity” of a collection of objects can be recursively generated from more fundamental information about the dissimilarity-distance between any pair of objects in the set. The diversity function is shown to satisfy a basic dynamic programming equation, which in a well-defined sense generates an optimal classification scheme. A surprisingly rich theory of diversity emerges, having ramifications for several disciplines. Implications and applications are discussed.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2118476
ER  - 



